📚 Portfolio Chatbot
A Complete Beginner's Guide
Line-by-line explanation of every file
Written for absolute beginners. No experience needed.

🏗️ What Are We Building?
We are building a personal portfolio chatbot — a web page that HR or employers can open in their browser, type questions about you, and get answers automatically.

It has 3 parts that work together:
• about_me.json — a file that stores all your personal information
• app.py — a Python program that runs the web server and logic
• index.html — the web page that people see in their browser

💡 NOTE: Think of it like this: index.html is the face, app.py is the brain, and about_me.json is the memory.

📄 Part 1: about_me.json
This file stores all your personal information. JSON stands for JavaScript Object Notation. It is just a way of organizing information using labels and values.

What does JSON look like?
{
  "name": "Your Name",
  "skills": "Python, Flask, HTML"
}

The label on the left (like "name") is called a KEY. The value on the right (like "Your Name") is the VALUE. They are separated by a colon. Every pair except the last one ends with a comma.

Line by line — about_me.json
{
This opens the JSON file. Everything goes inside these curly braces { }.

"name": "Your Name",
This stores your name. Replace "Your Name" with your actual name. The word name is the key (label), and Your Name is the value (your answer).

"age": "22",
This stores your age. Notice it is inside quotes — in this project we store everything as text to keep things simple.

"location": "Manila, Philippines",
Where you are based. HR might ask "Where are you from?" and this is what will be shown.

"education": "Bachelor of Science in Computer Science...",
Your educational background. Write it in a sentence that reads naturally — for example: Bachelor of Science in Computer Science, University of Santo Tomas, 2024.

"skills": "Python, HTML, CSS, JavaScript, FastAPI, PostgreSQL, Git",
List your technical skills separated by commas. This is what shows up when HR asks "What are your skills?"

"experience": "I built a To-Do CLI app...",
A short description of what you have done so far. Even personal projects count as experience when you are just starting out.

"projects": "1. To-Do CLI App... 2. Portfolio Chatbot...",
List your projects here. Number them so they are easy to read.

"why_hire": "I am self-taught, highly motivated...",
This is your elevator pitch — the answer to the most important HR question: Why should we hire you? Write something honest and confident.

}
This closes the JSON file. Do not forget this closing curly brace.

💡 NOTE: You only need to edit this file to update your info. You never have to touch app.py or index.html again once everything is set up.

🐍 Part 2: app.py
This is the Python file — the brain of the project. It does three things: loads your info from about_me.json, figures out what question was asked, and sends back the right answer.

What is Flask?
Flask is a Python library that lets you create a web server — a program that listens for requests from a browser and sends back responses. When someone opens your chatbot in a browser and clicks Send, Flask receives that message and handles it.

💡 NOTE: A library is code someone else already wrote that you can use in your own project. You install it once and then import it.

Line by line — the imports
from flask import Flask, render_template, request, jsonify
This line imports tools from the Flask library. Think of it like opening a toolbox and taking out specific tools you need:
• Flask — the main tool that creates your web server
• render_template — sends the HTML page to the browser
• request — reads the message sent from the browser
• jsonify — converts Python data into JSON format to send back

import json
This imports Python's built-in JSON tool. We use it to read your about_me.json file.

import os
This imports Python's operating system tool. We use it to check if the about_me.json file exists before trying to open it.

Line by line — setting up Flask
app = Flask(__name__)
This creates your web server and stores it in a variable called app. The __name__ part tells Flask where to look for files. You will see this line in every Flask project — it is always written exactly like this.

Line by line — load_tasks function
def load_about():
This defines a function called load_about. A function is a block of code that does one specific job. This function's job is to open about_me.json and return all your information.

    with open("about_me.json", "r") as f:
This opens the file about_me.json in read mode (that is what the "r" means). The with keyword makes sure the file is properly closed after we are done reading it — even if something goes wrong.

        return json.load(f)
This reads the JSON file and converts it into a Python dictionary (a collection of key-value pairs), then returns it so the rest of the code can use it.

Line by line — get_answer function
def get_answer(question, about):
This is the most important function. It takes two inputs: the question the HR person typed, and your about information. It then figures out which answer to return.

    q = question.lower().strip()
This converts the question to all lowercase letters and removes any extra spaces at the beginning or end. We do this so that "What are your SKILLS?" and "what are your skills?" are treated the same way.

    if any(word in q for word in ["hi", "hello", "hey"]):
This checks if any of the words hi, hello, or hey appear in the question. The any() function returns True if at least one of the words is found. This is how keyword matching works — we look for specific words in the question.

        return f"Hello! I'm {about['name']}'s portfolio chatbot..."
If a greeting was detected, we return a greeting response. The f at the start means it is an f-string — it lets us insert variables directly into the text using curly braces { }. So {about['name']} gets replaced with your actual name.

The rest of the function follows the same pattern for each topic: check if certain keywords appear in the question, then return the matching piece of info from your about_me.json.

    return "I'm not sure about that. Try asking about my skills..."
This is the fallback — if no keywords matched at all, we return this default message. Every chatbot needs a fallback for questions it does not understand.

Line by line — the routes
@app.route("/")
def index():
    return render_template('index.html')
A route tells Flask what to do when someone visits a specific URL. The @app.route("/") means: when someone visits the homepage (just the main URL with nothing after it), run the index function. That function sends the index.html file to the browser.

@app.route("/ask", methods=["POST"])
def ask():
This creates a second route at /ask. It only accepts POST requests — that means it only runs when data is being sent to it (not when someone just visits the URL). This is where the chat message from the browser gets processed.

    data = request.get_json()
This reads the JSON data that was sent from the browser. When the user clicks Send, the browser sends the question as JSON data to this route.

    question = data.get("question", "")
This extracts the question from the data. The second argument "" is a default value — if no question was sent, it uses an empty string instead of crashing.

    about = load_about()
This calls our load_about function to get your personal info from about_me.json.

    answer = get_answer(question, about)
This calls our get_answer function, passing in the question and your info. It returns the answer string.

    return jsonify({"answer": answer})
This sends the answer back to the browser as JSON. The browser then displays it in the chat window.

Line by line — the entry point
if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)
This tells Python: only run the server if this file is being run directly (not imported by another file). debug=True means the server will automatically restart whenever you save changes to the code — very helpful during development.

💡 NOTE: You will see if __name__ == "__main__" in almost every professional Python project. It is a standard pattern — always include it.

🌐 Part 3: index.html
This is the web page that people see in their browser. It is made of three parts: HTML (structure), CSS (design), and JavaScript (behavior).

What is HTML?
HTML is the skeleton of a web page. It defines what is on the page — a title, a chat box, an input field, a button. Every HTML element starts with an opening tag like <div> and ends with a closing tag like </div>.

What is CSS?
CSS is the styling. It controls how things look — colors, sizes, fonts, spacing, and layout. In this project, all the CSS is inside a <style> tag at the top of the file.

What is JavaScript?
JavaScript makes the page interactive. When the user clicks the Send button, JavaScript reads what they typed, sends it to app.py, waits for the answer, and displays it in the chat — all without refreshing the page.

Key HTML sections explained
<div id="chat-box">
This is the chat window where messages appear. It starts with one bot message already inside it: the welcome message. Every time the user sends a message, JavaScript adds new messages to this div.

<div class="suggestions">
These are the quick-tap suggestion chips at the bottom — buttons like Skills, Projects, Contact. When clicked, they automatically fill in and send a question. They make it easy for HR to explore without typing anything.

<input id="user-input" ...>
This is the text box where the user types their question. The onkeydown attribute listens for the Enter key — if Enter is pressed, it calls the sendMessage function automatically.

Key JavaScript functions explained
function addMessage(text, sender)
This function adds a new message bubble to the chat box. It creates a new div element, gives it the class user or bot (which controls the color and position), sets the text, and appends it to the chat box. It also scrolls the chat box to the bottom so the new message is always visible.

async function ask(question)
This function sends a question to app.py and displays the answer. The word async means this function can wait for a response without freezing the page. Here is what it does step by step:
• Calls addMessage to show the user's question in the chat
• Uses fetch() to send the question to the /ask route in app.py
• Waits for the response (the await keyword pauses here until the response arrives)
• Reads the answer from the response
• Calls addMessage again to display the bot's answer

async function sendMessage()
This function runs when the user clicks the Send button. It reads the text from the input box, clears the input box, and calls the ask function with the question.

💡 NOTE: The fetch() function is how JavaScript talks to your Python backend. It sends data to a URL and gets data back — all without refreshing the page. This is called an API call, and it is used everywhere in real web development.

🔗 How All 3 Files Connect
Here is the full journey of one message, from the moment the user types to the moment they see the answer:

• Step 1: The user types a question in index.html and clicks Send
• Step 2: JavaScript in index.html sends the question to the /ask route in app.py using fetch()
• Step 3: app.py receives the question and calls get_answer()
• Step 4: get_answer() checks the question for keywords and looks up the matching info from about_me.json
• Step 5: app.py sends the answer back to the browser as JSON
• Step 6: JavaScript in index.html receives the answer and displays it in the chat box

💡 NOTE: The browser and app.py talk to each other using JSON. The browser sends JSON (the question), and app.py sends JSON back (the answer). This JSON communication between a frontend and backend is used in almost every web app in the world.

▶️ How to Run the Project

Step 1 — Install Flask
Open your terminal (Command Prompt or VS Code terminal) and type:
pip install flask
This downloads and installs the Flask library onto your computer. You only need to do this once.

Step 2 — Set up your files
Create a folder called portfolio_chatbot. Inside it, create:
• app.py — paste the Python code
• about_me.json — paste the JSON and fill in YOUR information
• A folder called templates — create this folder
• Inside templates, create index.html — paste the HTML code

Step 3 — Run the server
In your terminal, navigate to your folder and type:
python app.py
You should see something like: Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000

Step 4 — Open in browser
Open your web browser and go to:
http://127.0.0.1:5000
Your chatbot should appear! Try clicking the suggestion chips or typing a question.

💡 NOTE: 127.0.0.1 means your own computer. Port 5000 is where Flask runs by default. This only works on your machine right now — deploying makes it work for everyone.

⚠️ Common Errors and How to Fix Them

ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'flask'
This means Flask is not installed. Fix: run pip install flask in your terminal.

FileNotFoundError: about_me.json
This means app.py cannot find your JSON file. Fix: make sure about_me.json is in the same folder as app.py, not inside the templates folder.

TemplateNotFound: index.html
Flask cannot find your HTML file. Fix: make sure index.html is inside a folder called templates. The folder name must be exactly templates, all lowercase.

SyntaxError in about_me.json
Your JSON has a formatting error. Common causes: a missing comma between entries, a missing closing quote, or a missing closing curly brace }. Fix: check each line carefully — every entry except the last one must end with a comma.

🚀 What's Next — Deploying Online
Right now your chatbot only works on your own computer. To share it with HR, you need to deploy it — put it on a server on the internet so anyone can visit it with a link.

The easiest free option is Render.com. Here is the process at a high level:
• Step 1: Create a free GitHub account and upload your project files
• Step 2: Create a free Render.com account
• Step 3: Connect your GitHub project to Render
• Step 4: Render gives you a live link like yourname.onrender.com
• Step 5: Share that link with HR!

💡 NOTE: GitHub is like Google Drive but for code. Render reads your code from GitHub and runs it on their servers. You will learn Git (the tool that uploads code to GitHub) as part of this step — it is an essential skill for every developer.

📖 Glossary — Words You Need to Know

Library
Code that someone else wrote that you can use in your project. Flask is a library. You install it with pip install.

Function
A named block of code that does one specific job. You define it once with def and call it whenever you need it.

Route
A URL path in a Flask app. When someone visits that URL, the matching function runs.

JSON
A format for storing and sending data using key-value pairs. Files end in .json. Python reads them with the json library.

API
A way for two programs to talk to each other. When JavaScript sends a question to Flask, it is making an API call.

Frontend
The part the user sees — in this project, that is index.html.

Backend
The part that runs on the server and handles logic — in this project, that is app.py.

Deploy
Putting your app on the internet so other people can access it from their own computers.

Debug mode
A setting in Flask (debug=True) that makes development easier by automatically restarting the server when you save changes.

Terminal / Command Prompt
The text-based window where you type commands to run Python, install libraries, and manage files.

